# â˜¸ï¸ Kubernetes Basic Commands

Kubernetes is a powerful container orchestration tool for automating deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications.  
Hereâ€™s a quick list of essential **kubectl** commands for your DevOps toolkit. 

---

## ğŸ§± Cluster & Context Management

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl version --short` | Show client and server version |
| `kubectl cluster-info` | Display cluster info |
| `kubectl config view` | View kubeconfig settings |
| `kubectl config get-contexts` | List all available contexts |
| `kubectl config use-context <context-name>` | Switch between clusters |
| `kubectl get nodes` | List all nodes in the cluster |

---

## ğŸ“¦ Pods

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl get pods` | List all pods in current namespace |
| `kubectl get pods -A` | List pods across all namespaces |
| `kubectl describe pod <pod-name>` | Show detailed pod info |
| `kubectl logs <pod-name>` | View pod logs |
| `kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name>` | View logs for a specific container |
| `kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- /bin/bash` | Access pod terminal |
| `kubectl delete pod <pod-name>` | Delete a pod |

---

## ğŸ—ï¸ Deployments

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl create deployment <name> --image=<image>` | Create a deployment |
| `kubectl get deployments` | List deployments |
| `kubectl describe deployment <name>` | Describe deployment details |
| `kubectl scale deployment <name> --replicas=<num>` | Scale a deployment |
| `kubectl set image deployment/<name> <container>=<image>` | Update container image |
| `kubectl rollout status deployment/<name>` | Check rollout status |
| `kubectl rollout undo deployment/<name>` | Rollback to previous version |
| `kubectl delete deployment <name>` | Delete a deployment |

---

## ğŸŒ Services

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl get svc` | List all services |
| `kubectl expose deployment <name> --type=NodePort --port=<port>` | Expose deployment as a service |
| `kubectl describe svc <name>` | Describe a service |
| `kubectl delete svc <name>` | Delete a service |

---

## ğŸ“ Namespaces

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl get ns` | List all namespaces |
| `kubectl create namespace <name>` | Create a namespace |
| `kubectl delete namespace <name>` | Delete a namespace |

---

## ğŸ§¾ ConfigMaps & Secrets

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl create configmap <name> --from-literal=<key>=<value>` | Create ConfigMap |
| `kubectl get configmaps` | List ConfigMaps |
| `kubectl describe configmap <name>` | Describe ConfigMap |
| `kubectl create secret generic <name> --from-literal=<key>=<value>` | Create Secret |
| `kubectl get secrets` | List secrets |
| `kubectl describe secret <name>` | Describe Secret |

---

## ğŸ§¹ Cleanup

| Command | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `kubectl delete all --all` | Delete all resources in namespace |
| `kubectl delete -f <file>.yaml` | Delete resources from file |

---

### âœ… Bonus
To apply or delete configurations via YAML files:
```bash
kubectl apply -f <file>.yaml
kubectl delete -f <file>.yaml
